description: $$Csummary$$VIn his introduction Professor Hibbard explains the process by which variant texts were fused in the 18th century to create the most commonly used text of today. Drawing on critical and theatrical history, he shows how this fusion makes 'Hamlet' seem a much more 'problematic' play than it was when it originally appeared in 1623.

abstract: In his introduction Professor Hibbard explains the process by which variant texts were fused in the 18th century to create the most commonly used text of today. Drawing on critical and theatrical history, he shows how this fusion makes 'Hamlet' seem a much more 'problematic' play than it was when it originally appeared in 1623.

description: $$Ccontents$$VThe Tragical History of Hamlet, Prince of Denmark The Second Quarto (1604-5) 169.

$$Csummary$$V"This Arden edition of Hamlet, arguably Shakespeare's greatest tragedy, presents an authoritative, modernized text based on the Second Quarto text with a new introductory essay covering key productions and criticism in the decade since its first publication. A timely up-date in the 400th anniversary year of Shakespeare's death which will ensure the Arden edition continues to offer students a comprehensive and current critical account of the play, alongside the most reliable and fully-annotated text available."--Publisher's description.

general: William Shakespeare at head of title.
The first translation of Hamlet into Portuguese, translated by King Luis I of Portugal.

NYU Abu Dhabi Special Collections copy 1 is a presentation copy. Presentation inscription of King Luis I to Al Emo. Sr. Don Matias de Velasco y Rojas, Marqués de Dos Hermanas--front flyleaf. Bound in full green leather contemporary binding ('Lisboa & Companhia') in pebbled morocco, gilt decorative elements and turn ins, all edges gilt, white moiré endpapers. Accompanied by 1 leaf of correspondence, dated 22 de Noviembre del 1879, from the Spanish legation in Lisbon, informing the Marqués de Dos Hermanas of the gift of a copy of the Portuguese King's translation of The Merchant of Venice in 1879.

general: "...traduite par Eugène Morand et Marcel Schwob et représentée pour la première fois au théatre Sarah Bernhardt en mai MDCCCXCIX"--page [1]

"Ce livre, le sixième de la collection du "Théatre d'art", a éré établi par Ad. van Bever. Tiré a mille neuf cent cinquante-six exemplaires, soit: 36 ex. sur vieux japon impérial, dont 8 hors commerce, numérotés de 1 a 28 et de 29 a 36; 20 ex. sur de chine, numérotés de 37 a 56; et 1900 ex. sur papier vélin des manufactures des rives (dont 100 hors commerce), numérotés de 57 a 1856 et de 1857 a 1956, le présent ouvrage a été achevé d'imprimer par l'Imprimerie Lux, a Paris, le xxvi janvier mcmxx."
Title page layout differs slightly for special printings.
Abu Dhabi Special Collections copy is "Exemplaire sur vélin de Rives No. 359."
